# Building Components

How to author your own component on top of Decor's base classes. Two paths:

1. **Single-skin component**: define one class under `Decor::Daisy::*` or `Decor::Suite::*` (or under your own namespace) that inherits from `Decor::PhlexComponent`.
2. **Two-skin component**: define an abstract base under your own namespace that owns the prop API, then two concrete subclasses that own the visual chrome.

## Prerequisites

Decor is built on [Phlex](https://phlex.fun), [Vident](https://github.com/stevegeek/vident), and [Literal](https://literal.fun). Quick refresher on what each contributes:

- **Phlex** — Ruby-native component DSL. The component renders by emitting elements directly to a buffer; no template files.
- **Vident** — adds Stimulus integration, root-element handling, child-element helpers, stable IDs, caching.
- **Literal** — typed props enforced at instantiation, plus type matchers (`_Nilable`, `_Union`, `_Array`, `_Boolean`, etc.).

## Base class

All Decor components inherit from `Decor::PhlexComponent`, which itself extends `Vident::Phlex::HTML` and pulls in shared concerns:

- `Decor::Concerns::SizeClasses` (`size` prop + `component_size_classes(size)` hook)
- `Decor::Concerns::ColorClasses` (`color` prop + `component_color_classes(color)` hook)
- `Decor::Concerns::StyleClasses` (`style` prop + `component_style_classes(style)` hook)

So every component you author gets `size`, `color`, and `style` props for free.

## Single-skin component

The simplest case — one class, one chrome.

```ruby
module MyApp
  class Pill < Decor::PhlexComponent
    no_stimulus_controller

    prop :label, String
    prop :icon, _Nilable(String)

    default_size :sm
    default_color :neutral
    default_style :filled

    def view_template
      root_element do
        if @icon
          render Decor::Icon.new(name: @icon, html_options: { class: "decor:w-3 decor:h-3 decor:mr-1" })
        end
        span { plain @label }
      end
    end

    private

    def root_element_classes
      ["decor:inline-flex decor:items-center decor:rounded-full", size_classes, color_classes, style_classes].join(" ")
    end

    def component_size_classes(size)
      case size
      when :xs then "decor:px-1.5 decor:py-0.5 decor:text-xs"
      when :sm then "decor:px-2 decor:py-0.5 decor:text-xs"
      when :md then "decor:px-2.5 decor:py-1 decor:text-sm"
      end
    end

    def component_color_classes(color)
      case color
      when :primary then "decor:bg-primary/10 decor:text-primary"
      when :success then "decor:bg-success/10 decor:text-success"
      else "decor:bg-base-200 decor:text-base-content"
      end
    end

    def component_style_classes(style)
      case style
      when :outlined then "decor:border"
      else ""
      end
    end
  end
end
```

Key Vident APIs used:
- `root_element { … }` — emits the component's root tag with controller binding + computed classes.
- `root_element_classes` — return value is joined into the root tag's `class` attribute.
- `no_stimulus_controller` — opts out of Vident emitting a `data-controller` attribute.

## Two-skin component

Use this when the same prop API needs distinct chrome per skin (the pattern Decor uses internally). Define an abstract base that owns the props and any skin-independent logic, then concrete skin subclasses.

```ruby
# abstract base — owns the prop API
module MyApp
  module Components
    class Pill < Decor::PhlexComponent
      no_stimulus_controller

      prop :label, String
      prop :icon, _Nilable(String)
    end
  end
end

# Daisy skin
module MyApp
  module Daisy
    class Pill < MyApp::Components::Pill
      def view_template
        root_element do
          render Decor::Icon.new(name: @icon, html_options: { class: "decor:w-3 decor:h-3 decor:mr-1" }) if @icon
          span { plain @label }
        end
      end

      private

      def root_element_classes
        "decor:d-badge decor:d-badge-neutral"
      end
    end
  end
end

# Suite skin
module MyApp
  module Suite
    class Pill < MyApp::Components::Pill
      def view_template
        root_element do
          render Decor::Icon.new(name: @icon, html_options: { class: "decor:w-3 decor:h-3 decor:mr-1" }) if @icon
          span(class: "decor:suite-caption") { plain @label }
        end
      end

      private

      def root_element_classes
        "decor:inline-flex decor:items-center decor:gap-1 decor:px-2 decor:rounded-suite-control decor:bg-suite-gray-25 decor:border decor:border-suite-hairline"
      end
    end
  end
end
```

If you only need different default values per skin (not different chrome), you can stay with the single-skin form and just have the consumer pass the right `color` / `style`.

## Stimulus integration

When a component needs JS behaviour, declare its controller wiring via Vident's `stimulus` DSL. Place the controller's JS file next to the Ruby class (e.g. `app/javascript/controllers/my_app/pill_controller.js`).

```ruby
class MyApp::Pill < Decor::PhlexComponent
  prop :open, _Boolean, default: false

  stimulus do
    targets :panel
    actions :toggle, :close
    values open: -> { @open }
    classes expanded: "decor:max-h-96", collapsed: "decor:max-h-0"
  end

  def view_template
    root_element do |el|
      button(data: { **el.stimulus_action(:click, :toggle) }) { plain "Toggle" }
      div(data: { **el.stimulus_target(:panel) }) do
        yield
      end
    end
  end
end
```

The `el` block argument gives you the Vident element with `stimulus_action`, `stimulus_target`, `stimulus_outlet`, `stimulus_value` helpers — the canonical way to emit `data-…-action` / `data-…-target` attributes that match the controller's identifier.

For components that don't need JS, opt out:

```ruby
no_stimulus_controller
```

## Redefining the standard props

If your component's `style` or `color` set should differ from the defaults, redefine at the class level:

```ruby
class MyApp::StatusIndicator < Decor::PhlexComponent
  redefine_styles :online, :offline, :busy, :away
  default_style :online

  def component_style_classes(style)
    case style
    when :online then "decor:bg-success"
    when :offline then "decor:bg-base-300"
    when :busy then "decor:bg-error"
    when :away then "decor:bg-warning"
    end
  end
end
```

`redefine_sizes` and `redefine_colors` work the same way. Prefer keeping the standard sets where reasonable — consumers learn a single vocabulary.

## URL props

If your component takes an `href` (or similar) and inherits from `Decor::PhlexComponent`, include `Decor::Concerns::ActsAsLink`. This brings in the `href`, `target`, `data`, `http_method`, `turbo_frame`, `turbo_prefetch`, `turbo_confirm`, `turbo` props, and applies the `safe_href` filter (strips `data:` / `vbscript:` schemes; Phlex 2.4 handles `javascript:` itself).

```ruby
class MyApp::Card < Decor::PhlexComponent
  include Decor::Concerns::ActsAsLink

  prop :title, String

  def view_template
    root_element do
      h3 { plain @title }
    end
  end

  private

  def link_element_tag
    :a # or :button, etc.
  end
end
```

## Caching

For components that are expensive to render and stable across requests, opt in to Vident's caching:

```ruby
class MyApp::DataTile < Decor::PhlexComponent
  with_cache_key

  prop :items, _Array(_Any)

  private

  def cache_key
    [self.class.name, @items.map(&:id), @size, @color, @style]
  end
end
```

## Slots

Vident provides `with_*` slot methods for content blocks. Declare them with `accepts_blocks` or define your own setter:

```ruby
class MyApp::Card < Decor::PhlexComponent
  prop :title, String

  def with_footer(&block)
    @footer = block
  end

  def view_template
    root_element do
      h3 { plain @title }
      yield if block_given?
      div(class: "decor:bg-suite-gray-25") { @footer.call } if @footer
    end
  end
end
```

## Testing

Decor uses `ActiveSupport::TestCase` (see `test/test_helper.rb`) with helpers for rendering Phlex components:

```ruby
require "test_helper"

class MyApp::PillTest < ActiveSupport::TestCase
  test "renders the label" do
    html = render_component(MyApp::Pill.new(label: "New"))
    assert_includes html, "New"
  end

  test "filled style emits the bg utility" do
    fragment = render_fragment(MyApp::Pill.new(label: "X", style: :filled, color: :primary))
    assert fragment.at_css("[class~='decor:bg-primary/10']")
  end
end
```

`render_component` returns the rendered HTML as a string; `render_fragment` returns a `Nokogiri::HTML5::DocumentFragment` for selector-based assertions. Note the colon-escaping in CSS selectors — `[class~='decor:foo']` is easiest since the literal colon in class names confuses naive `.decor:foo` selectors.

## Authoring a Lookbook preview

Drop a preview file at `test/components/previews/decor/<skin>/<component>_preview.rb` (or your own namespace). For inline scenarios that render a single component, the standard pattern works:

```ruby
class MyApp::Daisy::PillPreview < ::Lookbook::Preview
  # @label Default
  def default
    render MyApp::Daisy::Pill.new(label: "New")
  end
end
```

For scenarios that compose multiple components or have inline blocks, prefer a `render_with_template` + ERB file rather than nesting `render` calls in Ruby — `Lookbook::Preview#render` returns a Hash, and the block captured by it would stringify that Hash if you called `render` again inside. The ERB form handles `<%= render Other.new %>` correctly.

```ruby
# preview class
class MyApp::Daisy::PillPreview < ::Lookbook::Preview
  # @label Composed
  def composed
    render_with_template
  end
end

# matching ERB at test/components/previews/.../pill_preview/composed.html.erb
# <div class="decor:flex decor:gap-2">
#   <%= render MyApp::Daisy::Pill.new(label: "One") %>
#   <%= render MyApp::Daisy::Pill.new(label: "Two") %>
# </div>
```

